Social Networks and Spatial Mobility

Lika Zhvania | 29.08.2022

MSc thesis:
‘Connecting social network to mobility - comparison of the spatial pattern of mobility and the location of call partners based on passive mobile positioning dataset’

MSc, Geoinformatics for Urbanised Society
Department of Geography, University of Tartu

1 Project description

2 Data

2.1 Data description

The primary data which is used in the thesis research, is the passive mobile positioning data, in particular, Call Detail Records (CDR), Call Graph. The data is obtained by the mobile network operators and contains information about the time and location of the call, identifications of the call initiator and receiver. The locations of the calls are aggregated by the closest antenna that receives the signal from while calling. The data has dyadic characteristics.

2.5 Settlement types

Settlements contain the information about type

Settlement type is coded by EHAK as follows:

0 - county
1 - rural municipality
3 - town
4 - city
5 - city without municipal status
6 - city district
7 - small town
8 - village

Data source: Geoportal, Republic of Estonia LAND BOARD
Geoportal

Check unique values of settlement types to see which types are represented in the dataset

settl_types_UV <- unique(settl$TYYP)

cat(' The codes indicating the types of settlements of Estonia, are following:', sort(as.integer(settl_types_UV)))
##  The codes indicating the types of settlements of Estonia, are following: 3 4 5 6 7 8

Assign appropriate type names to EHAK codes in new fields called settl_type (urban & rural) and settl_hier (urban: big city, urban: small city, rural)

# Settlement types
# Urban
urban <- settl$TYYP %in% c(3, 4, 5, 6, 7)
# Rural
rural <- settl$TYYP %in% c(8)
# assign new values
settl$settl_type[urban] <- "urban"
settl$settl_type[rural] <- "rural"


settl$settl_hier <- settl$settl_type
settl$settl_hier <- ifelse(settl$settl_hier == 'urban', 'urban: small city', settl$settl_hier)


# Big cities: Tallinn, Tartu, Narva, Pärnu, Kohtla-Järve, Jõhvi
# Tallinn
settl$settl_hier <- ifelse(settl$ONIMI == 'Tallinn', 'urban: big city', settl$settl_hier)
# Tartu
settl$settl_hier <- ifelse(settl$ONIMI == 'Tartu linn' & settl$TYYP == '5', 'urban: big city', settl$settl_hier)
# Narva
settl$settl_hier <- ifelse(settl$ONIMI == 'Narva linn', 'urban: big city', settl$settl_hier)
# Pärnu
settl$settl_hier <- ifelse(settl$ONIMI == 'Pärnu linn' & settl$TYYP == '5', 'urban: big city', settl$settl_hier)
# Kohtla-Järve
settl$settl_hier <- ifelse(settl$ONIMI == 'Kohtla-Järve linn', 'urban: big city', settl$settl_hier)
# Jõhvi
settl$settl_hier <- ifelse(settl$ONIMI == 'Jõhvi vald' & settl$TYYP == '5', 'urban: big city', settl$settl_hier)
# check newly assigned fields
head(settl, 1)

3.1 Fix coordinates and rename columns

# fix coordinates
mob_data <- mob_data %>% 
  mutate(
    lon_x = as.character(lat) %>% 
      str_pad(3, side = "left", pad = "0") %>% 
      str_replace("(\\w{2})", "\\1\\.") %>% 
      as.numeric(), 
    lat_y = as.character(lon) %>% 
      str_pad(3, side = "left", pad = "0") %>% 
      str_replace("(\\w{2})", "\\1\\.") %>% 
      as.numeric()
  )

To make dataset headers readable, it is better to change the names of the first and second users ‘op_pos_usr_id’ is replaced with ‘caller’ & ‘op_pos_usr_id_rec’ with ‘callee’

3.2 Time variables

Create time variables

# time variables
mob_data <- mob_data %>% 
  mutate(
    year = year(pos_time), 
    month = month(pos_time), 
    day = day(pos_time), 
    wday = lubridate::wday(pos_time, label = FALSE, week_start = getOption("lubridate.week.start", 1)), 
    wday_attr = lubridate::wday(pos_time, label = TRUE, abbr = FALSE), 
    hour = hour(pos_time), 
    hour_rounded = hour(round_date(pos_time, "hour")), 
    min = minute(pos_time), 
    sec = second(pos_time), 
    hour_min = hour + min/60
  )

Sort mobile data by user id (caller) and time

mob_data <- mob_data[order(mob_data$caller, mob_data$pos_time), ]

3.3 Join mobile dataset with settlement types

First, create x/y fields to use them for creating geometry and keep also them separately

mob_data <- mob_data %>% 
  mutate(x = lon_x, 
         y = lat_y)

Convert data to sf format to use it later for joining

mob_data_sf <- st_as_sf(mob_data, coords = c("x", "y"),  crs = 4326)  %>% 
  st_transform(crs = 3301)

Join mobile data with settlement types by using st_join() and join = st_intersects for ‘point in polygon’ spatial relationship

joined <- st_join(mob_data_sf, settl, 
                  join = st_intersects, 
                  left = TRUE)

Locate x/y from geometry into separate column by using unlist() and map()

joined <- joined %>% 
  mutate(x = unlist(map(joined$geometry, 1)), 
         y = unlist(map(joined$geometry, 2)))

Drop the geometry column

mob_data <- joined %>% 
  st_drop_geometry()

# In 'hour_rounded' variable, for midnight zero (0) is assigned. However, as I have removed all the variables under 6 AM, there is
# a gap between midnight and 6 AM, thus it is more reseanable to to give new value that is 24 to midnight instead of 0
mob_data$hour_rounded <- ifelse(mob_data$hour_rounded == 0, 24, mob_data$hour_rounded)

50% of calls from the same antennas are made only for one day, 75% are made for three days. We can’t assume the antenna as home location if calling activitiy from it is made only once, twice or three times, as it contains the possibility of irregular, random call activity and not necessarily refer to frequent calling behaviour of the caller.

/nWe need to omit the observations of 2-day calling activities

7.2 Create a graph

Create matrix

sn_edges <- edge_weight %>% 
  select(Source, Target)

sn.mat <- as.matrix(sn_edges)

Create graph

sn_g <- graph.edgelist(sn.mat, directed = TRUE)

#V(sn_g)
#E(sn_g)
# Count number of edges
gsize(sn_g)
## [1] 1667294
# Count number of vertiices
gorder(sn_g)
## [1] 332698

Give attributes to nodes

settl_type <- nodes$settl_type
settl_hier <- nodes$settl_hier
x <- nodes$x
y <- nodes$y
lon <- nodes$lon
lat <- nodes$lat

# create new vertex attributes
sn_g <- set_vertex_attr(sn_g, 'settl_type', value = settl_type)
sn_g <- set_vertex_attr(sn_g, 'settl_hier', value = settl_hier)
sn_g <- set_vertex_attr(sn_g, 'x', value = x)
sn_g <- set_vertex_attr(sn_g, 'y', value = y)
sn_g <- set_vertex_attr(sn_g, 'lon', value = lon)
sn_g <- set_vertex_attr(sn_g, 'lat', value = lat)

Give attributes to links

dist_km <- edge_weight$dist_km
settl_type_pairs <- edge_weight$settl_type_pairs
settl_hier_pairs <- edge_weight$settl_hier_pairs
weight <- edge_weight$weight

# create edge attributes
sn_g <- set_edge_attr(sn_g, 'dist_km', value = dist_km)
sn_g <- set_edge_attr(sn_g, 'settl_type_pairs', value = settl_type_pairs)
sn_g <- set_edge_attr(sn_g, 'settl_hier_pairs', value = settl_hier_pairs)
sn_g <- set_edge_attr(sn_g, 'weight', value = weight)

8 Node degrees

Function degree() has: ‘in-degree’, ‘out-degree’ and ‘all’ or ‘total’ modes

# Calculate node degree with modes: all, in, out
V(sn_g)$degree <- igraph::degree(sn_g, mode = "all")
V(sn_g)$degree_in <- igraph::degree(sn_g, mode = "in")
V(sn_g)$degree_out <- igraph::degree(sn_g, mode = "out")
# Subgraphs according to settlement types
sn_g_urb_bigcity <- induced_subgraph(sn_g, V(sn_g)[settl_hier=='urban: big city'])
sn_g_urb_smallcity <- induced_subgraph(sn_g, V(sn_g)[settl_hier=='urban: small city'])
sn_g_rural <- induced_subgraph(sn_g, V(sn_g)[settl_hier=='rural'])

Plot node degree distribution

#dev.cur()

# All

     probability = TRUE, 
     main = "Whole dataset", 
     xlab = 'log(Degree mode: all)', 
     border = "#737373",

     )

     col = "#737373",
